I have a product landing page for 'Helix' (a macOS menu bar app for mutagen file sync). The page has an arctic white theme with blue (#3194d0) and teal (#3dbcb0) accents. Currently there's a subtle 3D Three.js DNA double helix rotating slowly on the right side of the page as a decorative background element. It works but it's underwhelming — just a thin rotating wireframe-ish helix at low opacity. I want to make this dramatically more impressive while still being a background decoration (not distracting from content). The helix should clearly evoke DNA/double helix imagery. The page is a single static HTML file with inline CSS and Three.js loaded via CDN script tag (three@0.160.0). What are the most visually striking approaches to render a DNA helix background that would make someone go 'wow' when they first load the page? Consider: shaders, particle effects, glow effects, strand thickness, camera angles, depth of field, color gradients along strands, glass/translucent materials, bloom, etc. Give me specific Three.js implementation strategies with code snippets, not vague ideas.

response:
Below are **concrete Three.js recipes** you can drop into your existing `<script>` block to turn that whisper‑thin helix into a “wow”‑inducing background—complete with glowing strands, volumetric fog, animated particles, depth‑of‑field and custom shaders for smooth color gradients. Each recipe assumes you already have the basic scene, camera, light and render‑loop from your current code (lines ~270–375 in your file). You can pick and choose or combine them.

---

## 1. Add a bloom/glow post‑processing pass

A simple but powerful way to make your helix “pop” is to render it to a separate scene layer and apply a bloom (glow) pass. This will make the strands glow softly against the background.

```js
// ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// 1) Import EffectComposer, RenderPass & UnrealBloomPass from CDN (after three.min.js)
const { EffectComposer } = THREE;
const { RenderPass }       = THREE;
const { UnrealBloomPass }  = THREE;

// 2) Create composer & passes (insert after your renderer, scene, camera setup)
const composer = new EffectComposer(renderer);
composer.addPass(new RenderPass(scene, camera));
const bloomPass = new UnrealBloomPass(
  new THREE.Vector2(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight),
  /* strength */ 0.6,
  /* radius */   0.4,
  /* threshold*/ 0.2
);
composer.addPass(bloomPass);

// 3) In your animate() loop, replace renderer.render(...) with composer.render()
function animate() {
  requestAnimationFrame(animate);
  group.rotation.y += 0.002;
  composer.render();
}
animate();
